        <page n="01" image="pa.fr.vs.1861.07.03.01">
            <div type="a">
                <column>01</column>
                <head>War News--Important from Matthias' Point</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Account of a skirmish at Matthias Point. Four Union men were wounded when
                    they were attacked while digging earthworks.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>01</column>
                <head>From Baltimore</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>The public is quite feverish with excitement in Baltimore over the
                    developments under the new police regime.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>02</column>
                <head>Southern Intelligence via Louisville</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>A correspondence appeared in the Louisville newspaper between Gen. Buckner
                    and the Quartermaster of the State Guards. Collector Colton and W.P. Weller, the
                    special agent of the government, were accused of refusing to allow supplies to
                    the troops at Columbus to pass by river or railroad.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>02</column>
                <head>Skirmish Near Cumberland</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Account of a skirmish between Union pickets and Confederate cavalry near
                    Romney. The pickets were able to learn that there were four regiments of
                    Confederates near Romney.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <pageNote>Miscellaneous war news</pageNote>
        </page>
        <page n="02" image="pa.fr.vs.1861.07.03.02">
            <div type="a">
                <column>01</column>
                <head>The Fourth</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>There are no plans for any organized celebrations of the Fourth of July due
                    to the war.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>01</column>
                <head>The Wheat Crop</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>The wheat harvest in the county promises to be very good.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>01</column>
                <head>False Reports</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>The rumor that two of the picket guards on the Franklin Railroad have been
                    shot is false. The Spirit criticizes those who spread such unfounded and
                    hysterical war news.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>01</column>
                <head>Relief Fund</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Announces that the County Commissioners appropriated money to support the
                    families of the local volunteers for four weeks.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>02</column>
                <head>Sick Soldiers</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>The sick soldiers who had been quartered at Franklin Hall have been
                    removed. Many local families have taken in two or three convalescing soldiers.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>02</column>
                <head>In Town</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Capt. Housum of Company A, Second Regiment, Penna. visited his home and
                    reported that the Franklin men are doing well.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>02</column>
                <head>Infanticide</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Mary Starlipper, an employee of Fisher's Hotel, gave birth to a child and
                    concealed it in a bucket. She claimed it was still-born, but the medical
                    examiner found that the child was born alive. She will be arrested and taken to
                    prison.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>03</column>
                <head>Congress</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt>"There is . . . no hope for the nation--nothing before us but a long and
                    bloody war."</excerpt>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>The Spirit believes that Congress will not favor any peace measures when it
                    convenes next week.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>03</column>
                <head>Latest News</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Capt. McMullen's Rangers left a company flag in the hands of Squire Hamman
                    when they left Franklin County. They instructed him to display it whenever good
                    news was heard from the Rangers. The flag will thus be displayed from the
                    veranda of the Franklin House now that Chambersburg has received news that the
                    Rangers have successfully advanced into Virginia.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <pageNote/>
        </page>
